In article <16BBF14CD5.C445585@mizzou1.missouri.edu>, C445585@mizzou1.missouri.edu (John Kelsey) writes:
|> 1.  If the pad's really random, then one-time pad encryption is provably
|> secure.
|>  
|> 2.  If your one-time-pad is really random, then *any* method of mapping
|> A op B = C; B other_op C = A   will work.  (For XORing, op = other_op = XOR)
|>  [...]

Not *any* : A op B = A doesn't encypher anything. For all A, B --> A op B need to be a
1-1 function.

  --Serge Vaudenay
